Human Decision Point(s): There were a few times when I got an error after the code it gave me, which it then had to redo and try again. I also changed all of the colours of the generated items after the fact, not simply relying on the colours the AI generated for me, as they didn't fit my vision. However, one of the biggest decisions for me was the spikes at the top of the screen. This is not necessarily the fault of the AI, however moreso because I wasn't confident in my prompts and the outcome I wanted from the spikes. I didn't just want them to be hanging there; I wanted them to be more interactive. This is when I remember the sushi go mechanics: you can choose certain cards each round, and I thought you could customize the level by deciding which spikes you wanted to keep and randomizing the heights. This took a couple of tries and adjustments to the mechanics to get to something I was happy with. I do want to clarify that all of the ideas for what to put in the game were mine, even the spiky balls hanging from the ceiling to amplify the feeling of anxiousness. 

